Let $C = \begin{bmatrix} a & d \\ b & e \\ c & f \end{bmatrix}$. Then
multiplying out the required matrix gives

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
= BC &= 
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & -1 \\ -3 & 1 & 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} a & d \\ b & e \\ c & f \end{bmatrix}\\
&= \begin{bmatrix} (1)(a)+(0)(b) + (-1)(c) & (1)(d) + (0)(e) + (-1)(f) \\ (-3)(a) + (1)(b) + (0)(c) & (-3)(d) + (1)(e) + (0)(f) \end{bmatrix}\\
&= \begin{bmatrix} a-c & d-f \\ -3a + b & -3d + e \end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

This gives the equations

\begin{align*}
a-c &= 1\\
d-f &= 0 \\
-3a + b &= 0 \\
-3d + e &= 1
\end{align*}

Setting simple values like $a=1$ and $e=1$ gives us that
$b=3,c=0,d=0,f=0$. This is a valid solution and thus such a matrix C
exists and is given by

$C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 3 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}$
